tAdoption Disruption -- tUnpacking Permanency for Youth: Overuse/Misuse of Another Planned Permanent Living Arrangement (APPLA) as a Permanency Goal -- tYouth Development and Transitional Living Services -- tFamily Foster Care -- tResidential Services -- tSibling Issues -- tVisits: Critical to the Well-Being and Permanency of Children and Youth in Care -- tPostpermanency Services -- tPART 4. SYSTEMIC ISSUES IN CHILD WELFARE -- tThe Child and Family Services Reviews -- tPlacement Stability -- tFoster Parent Recruitment, Retention, Development, and Support -- tLegal and Judicial Engagement -- tChild Welfare Workforce Issues -- tChild Welfare Supervision -- tResearch and Evaluation -- tDisproportionate Representation of Children and Youth -- tFatherhood -- tImmigrant Children, Youth, and Families -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Adoption and Safe Families Act (ASFA), which became law in 1997, elicited a major shift in federal policy and thinking toward child welfare, emphasizing children's safety, permanency, and well-being over preserving biological ties at all costs. The first edition of this volume mapped the field of child welfare after ASFA's passage, detailing the practices, policies, programs, and research affected by the legislation's new attitude toward care. This second edition highlights the continuously changing child welfare climate in the U.S., including content on the Fostering Connections Act of 2008.The authors have updated the text throughout, drawing from real-world case examples and data obtained from the national Child and Family Services Reviews and emerging empirically based practices. They have also added chapters addressing child welfare workforce issues, supervision, and research and evaluation. The volume is divided into four sections—child and adolescent well-being, child and adolescent safety, permanency for children and adolescents, and systemic issues within services, policies, and programs. Recognized scholars, practitioners, and policy makers discuss meaningful engagement with families, particularly Latino families; health care for children and youth, including mental health care; effective practices with LGBT youth and their families; placement stability; foster parent recruitment and retention; and the challenges of working with immigrant children, youth, and families.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChild welfarezUnited States. 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / Adoption & Fostering.2bisacsh1 aAckroyd, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen-Eckard, Kara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBecker, Melissa F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerg, Kristin L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerry, Marianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBossard, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraxton, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrittain, Charmaine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBullard, Lloyd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurke, Tracey K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoakley, Tanya M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Mary Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins-Camargo, Crystal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConway, Debra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCostello, Theresa, econtributor.4ctb4h